# HTML Element IDs

Every HTML element that is created must have a **unique, descriptive `id`** attribute set. No exceptions.

## Purpose

- Enables instructing UI changes by specific element (e.g. "change the text in the submit button" → target by id).
- Makes automation, testing, and AI-driven edits reliable and unambiguous.

## Requirements

1. **Every element gets an id** — `div`, `span`, `button`, `input`, `section`, `header`, `form`, etc.
2. **Unique** — No two elements in the same document (or same logical view) share the same id.
3. **Descriptive** — The id reflects the element’s role or content (e.g. `id="auth-form-submit-btn"`, not `id="btn1"`).

## Naming

- Use kebab-case: `id="user-profile-avatar"`.
- Prefer role + context: `id="settings-notifications-toggle"`, `id="checkout-shipping-address-input"`.
- For repeated items (lists), include a stable identifier: `id="todo-item-{id}"`, `id="product-card-{slug}"`.

## Examples

```html
<!-- ❌ BAD: no id -->
<button>Submit</button>
<div class="card">...</div>

<!-- ❌ BAD: non-descriptive or non-unique -->
<button id="btn">Submit</button>
<div id="div1">...</div>

<!-- ✅ GOOD: unique and descriptive -->
<button id="contact-form-submit-btn">Submit</button>
<section id="pricing-plans-section">...</section>
<input id="signup-email-input" type="email" />
```

In JSX/TSX, set `id` on every DOM element you render (including layout elements) so UI instructions can refer to them by id.
